==English==
===Etymology===
Old French [[ordure#French|ordure]], from [[ord#Old French|ord]] ‘filthy’, from Latin ''[[horridus]]'' ’horrid’, + [[-ure]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ɔ:djʊə/

===Noun===
{{en-noun|ordure|ordures}}
#[[excrement]], [[dung]]
#:*'''1988''': The bowels and bladder collapsed, sheets and mattress had to be burnt at the bottom of the back garden.  The body, having vulgarly shed its '''ordures''', now turned into an '''ordure''' itself. — Anthony Burgess, ''Any Old Iron''


